AI agents in healthcare are computational systems capable of perceiving their environment, making decisions, and taking actions to achieve specific goals within a medical setting \cite{russell2010artificial}. These agents can operate with varying degrees of autonomy, from decision support systems that assist clinicians to fully autonomous robotic surgery assistants. They often leverage Machine Learning and Deep Learning techniques to learn from data and improve their performance over time \cite{lecun2015deep}.

The scope of AI agents extends beyond simple automation; they are designed to exhibit intelligent behavior. This includes reasoning, problem-solving, and learning from experience. In healthcare, this means agents can adapt to new patient data, evolving medical guidelines, and changing clinical scenarios. Understanding their capabilities is crucial for appreciating their potential impact on patient outcomes and healthcare delivery \cite{davenport2019ai}.

